Bring a #saucepan{} of water up to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp} for the pasta. Trim the @courgette{1} then slice into rounds about 1cm thick. Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then slice thinly. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on a high heat (no oil). Once hot, add the courgette and cook on each side until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Remove from the pan to a clean chopping board or #plate{} and allow to cool.

Once the water for the pasta is boiling, add the @linguine{200%g} and simmer until tender, ~{12%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}, pop back in the pan, drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile return the frying pan to medium high heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, add the garlic and half of the chilli (use less if you don't like heat) and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}. Add the @tomato passata{1%jar}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, @water{75%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1%.} Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @king prawns{300%g} to the tomato sauce, stir together and simmer until cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop up the courgette and add to a #small bowl{} with the spring onion and remaining chilli (use less chilli if you don't like heat).

Add the drained pasta to the pan of tomato sauce along with the cheese. Mix well to combine, then season to taste with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Spoon over the charred courgette mixture. Enjoy!

> Tip: Add a splash more water if the liquid has evaporated too much.

== Step 5 MOD ==

> If you've chosen to get extra prawns, just cook the recipe as instructed.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.